{"/service/ndnp/mthi/batch_mthi_bison_ver01/data/sn83045217/00295860728/1921030301/0671.xml":{"full_text":"Owners of Elk Basin Shares\nAre Receiving Dividend,\nSome on Cat Creek Oil.\nSpecial to The Tribune.\nLewistpwn, March 2.\u2014The Wild\nschutz-Harrison Green Royalty asso\ndation filed its agreements, etc., with\nthe county clerk and recorder Tues\nJ day. The concern is capitalized for\n5175,000, the trustees being Matthias\nWildsch\u00fctz, Harrison Green and L. W.\nRobinson Jr.\nThe Continental Commercial Oil\ncompany filed its articles of incorpo\nration here Tuesday and will operate\nin Cat Creek. The company is cap\nitalized for $640,000, the incorporators\nbeing M. E. Olsby, D. A. Steward. Al\nford Hoon, R. H. See and C. G. Ross,\nall of Miles City.\nI\nThe Arrow Oil Syndicate has filed\nits articles, the concern being capital\nized for $60,000. The company owns\na tract in Cat Creek, the trustees be\ning Di^ A. W. Deal, C. E. King and\nDave Burnett, the latter formerly of\nGreat Falls.\nThe owners of the Elk Basin shares\nhere, received on the trade-in of\nJTrantz stock after the purchase of\nthe irantz Corporation by the Elk\nBasin, are receiving another dividend\non their holdings in the big company,\nana a lot of this money represents Cat\nCreek oil.\nFire Damages House\nat Belt; Starts From\nDefective Flue, Claim\nSpecial to The Tribune.\nBelt, March 2.\u2014Fire which broke out\nabout 9 o'clock last Friday morning\npartially destroyed tie residence of\nMrs. Hannah Waris in Belt. The fire\nstarted in the unused attic of the house\nand although the Belt volunteer fire\nmen were on hand in a short time\nmost of the roof of the house was\nburned. There was considerable dam\nage done because of water. It is\nthought the fir e started from a defec\ntive flue. The loss is covered by in\nsurance.\nEstimate Unemployed\nin Montana Cities\nin January at 3,000\nHelena, Mar. 2.--According to figures\nof the United States employment ser\nvices, there were approximately 3,000\npeople out of work during January in\nthe five large cities of Montana, whose\nestimated population is 105,000. Of\nthese 25 were in Helena. 350 in\nGreat Falls, 400 in Billings, 500 in\nMissoula and 1,750 in Butte.\nOrganize First Post\nof Disabled Montana\nVeterans at Bozeman\nBozeman, Alar. 2.\u2014The first post of\nthe \"National Disabled Veterans of the\nWorld War\" to be organized in Mon\ntana has been started here with 10\nmembers. Headquarters are in Cin\ncinnati, Ohio. Any man bearing a\nwound stripe is eligible, whether ac\ntually disabled or rot.\nitching\nPILES\nPAZO OINTMENT instantly Re\nlieves ITCHING PILES and you\ncan get restful sleep after the\nfirst application.\nAll druggists are authorized to\nrefund the money if PAZO OINT\nMENT fails to Cure any case of\nITCHING. BLIND, BLEEDING or\nPROTRUDING PILES. Cures or\ndinary cases in 6 days, the\nworst cases in 14 days.\nIt is guaranteed by Paris Med\nicine Co., St. Louis, Mo., Manu\nfacturers of the world-famous\nGrove's Laxative Bromo Quinine\ntablets.\n(O 'Jfc.fyrervt*\nThis signature is on every box\nof PAZO OINTMENT. 60c.\nm\nPERSONAL SUPERVISION\nGives\nQUALITY\nDENTISTRY\nIt Is Here for You at\nGreat Falls\nLARGEST\nDENTAL OFFICE\nDR.W.F.G1\nHours: 8:30 a. m.\nPhone 609\nFirst National]\nTake Elevator to\nMontana and Utah\nto Debate Japanese\nExclusion Question\nSpecial to The Tribune.\nMissoula. March 2.\u2014Arthur Redding\nand Matt Pearce of the debating squad\nof the university will meet the debate\nteam of the University of Utah in sup\nport of the Japanese exclusion ques\ntion in Missoula, March 3, the same\ntime as another team from the uni\nversity will meet a second Utah team\n\u00abt the University of Utah in support\nof the negative side of the question.\nThe second varsity team which will\ngo to Utah will be selected the fol\nlowing members of the debate team:\nKussel Niles, Delbert Cawley, Leo\nStewart and Harold Reynolds. The\nnext debate will be March 10 with\nWashington State college.\nWMBE\nL\nGeneral Sales Manager for\nWestern Woolgrowers Tells of\nNew Plans of Organization.\nSpecial to The Tribune.\nBozeman, March 2.\u2014Ray Hollowoy\nis in the city from Chicago for a few\ndays on business and is being inter\nviewed regarding the plans of the\nWestern Woolgrowers' association,\nfor which he is the general sales\nmanager. He was for many years a\nBozeman business man, and he says\nthat the association has gone into the\nbusiness of manufacturing cloth from\nMontana wool, and this cloth is being\nmade into suits that are now on the\nmarket and receiving a ready sale.\nMr. Holhjway is very enthusiastic\nabout the future of the business of the\nassociation, because he feels that it\nis important, to know that the cloth\nmanufactured by this association is the\nonly cloth that is guaranteed to be all\nAmerican virgin wool v with no shoddy.\nTo Make Ready-To-Wear Suits\nThe Montana wool, he states, is\nmade into cloth at. the factories and it\nis made into clothes now only at tailor\nshops on special order, but plans are\nbeing made for the manufacture of\nready-to-wear lines of suits.\nThe records show thaf at the pres\nent time the factories are turning\nout about 20,000 yards of cloth a\nweek and that orders are being re\nceived daily for a large number of\nsuits, and the tailor shops are filling\norders for about 1,800 suits a week.\nThe only suits made now are costing\nthe customers ?37 and $39, while suits\nfor children from eight years up retail\nfor about $12. The latter are ordered\ndirect.\nProvides Market on Wool.\nOne of the important features of\nthe business, Mr. Holloway believes,\nis the fact that a market has been\nprovided for one of the important pro\nducts of Montana, and that the public\nis getting the benefits of the movement\nin securing a high class article for a\nreasonable price.\nCut This Out\u2014It Is Worth Money.\nCut out this slip, enclose with 5c\nand mail it to Foley Co., 2835 Shef\nfield Ave., Chicago, 111., writing your\nname and address clearly. You will\nreceive in return a trial package con\ntaining Foley's Iloney and Tar Com\npound for coughs, colds and croup:\nFoley Kidney Pills for pains in sides\nand back; rheumatism, backache, kidi\nney and bladder ailments; and Foley\nCathartic Tablets, a wholesome and\nthoroughly cleansing cathartic for con\nstipation, biliousness, headaches, and\nsluggish bowels. Great Falls Drug\nCo.\u2014Adv.\nMany Greeks in Trans-Caucasia\nDie Each Day, Relief\nWorker Says.\nNew York.\u2014(Correspondence of The\nAssociated Press.) Six thousand\nGreek refugees, at Batum, Trans\nCaucasia, their clothing worn\nshreds, are \"living like wild animals I\nin dens\" and dying at the rate of from\n3;\"\u00bb to 50 a day, writes Dr. W. E.\nRambo, a Near -East Relief worker,\nof West Philadelphia, Pa., in a report\nfrom the Black Sea port received here.\nIn what he calls \"a tragic exodus\nthat bids to become historic,\" Dr.\nRambo says the Greek government al\nready has repatriated 20,000 who emi\ngrated from the Near East to colonize\nThrace and that from 10,000 to 12,000\nremain to be transported from Batum\nback to their homeland. Most of\nthese, he says, are physically strong\nbut 0,000 refugees from other regions\nwho flocked to Batum in the expec\ntation of relief have been in that city\nfive months, waiting in vain for help,\ntheir condition daily becoming more\ndesperate on account of the rigors\nof the present Georgian winter.\nThe Greek ,'jovernment, Dr. Rambo\nexplains, disclaiming responsibility for\nthe plight of the people, has undertak\nen through humane considerations\nonly to feed, an doctor the refugees\nbut, so far, has declined to transport\nthem to Greece on the ground that\nthere is insufficient housing there to\nshelter them.\n\"Meanwhile,\" the letter says, \"the\n6.000 are overcrowded in barracks\nunfit for human habitation. The fam\nilies have no privacy. Some are lying\nin bed day and night because they\nhave no clothing to protect them from\nthe cold or cover their nakedness.\nUnless speedy relief comes to these\npeople most of them will die during\nthe winter. Already the remnants ef\nthe original refugees are in despair.\nOne of them said to me: 'We are no\nlonger waiting for ships; wo are waiting\nfor death.' Of 5,767 in 'ibis party in\nthe beginning only about 2,400 remain\n\u20143,367 are dead. Another party of\n6,800 has 2,800 survivors\u20144,000 are\ndead. Of the survivors 700 are \u00fcl.\"\nSTRANGE AND WILD.\n\"Do t\u00e9ll lis about the Great Wild\nWest,\" said the impressionable young\nwoman.\nYou may not believe it,\" replied the\ntourist, \"but I found a little town in\nNorth Dakota where there was not a\nsingle motion-picture theater.\"\u2014 Bir\nmingham Age-Herald,\nIB STMT DRILLING\nIT KEVIN Wimm\nT\nGordon Campbell Co. Putting\nUp Derrick and Hauling\nTools to Site.\nSpecial to The Tribune.\nKevin, March 2.\u2014Oil activities in\nthe Kevin region are assuming large\nproportions. -The derrick timber for\nthe Gordon Campbell Co., is veing mov\ned to its location some three miles\nnorthwest of Kevin. Active 'drilling\nwill commence in ,the course of a few\ndays, as there is an abundant supply\nof water, and the bunk houses, and\ncook shack are completed. All that re\nmains to be done is to put up the\nderrick, and haul the tools to it, and\nthis is being accomplished as rapidly\nas men and horses can do the work.\nThere are a number of other com\npanies in the Kevin field that intend\nto have their drills working within\nthe next three months. It will be but\na short time until there will be about\n15 rigs operating in the immediate\nvicinity of Kevin.\nMany believe that the Kevin struc\nture is where the much sought after\n\"mother oil pool\" of Montana will be\nfound\nMethodists to Hold\nSpecial Services at\nBelt During Lent\nSpecial to The Tribune.\nBelt. March 2.\u2014Beginning next Sun\nday, March 6. the Methodist church of\nBelt is to have a series of special re\nvival meetings. The services will run\nuntil Easter and will be conducted by\nthe minester of the church, the Rev.\nAlvin F. Taylor. Dr. A. G. Bennett\nof the Great Falls Methodist church\nis expected out for one meeting and\nthe Rev. J. A. Martin may be present\nto assist a few nights.\nMeetings will be held every night\nduring the week except Monday and\nSaturday nights. A large chorus choir\nwill furnish special music during the\nseries.\nFALLS 1000 FEET IN\nYUKON, BREAKS 3 RIBS\nDawson, Yukon Teritory, \"March 2.\u2014\nFalling off a thousand foot bluff.^.Tack\nStewart .foreman at the New Ivenka\nhill silver mine in the Mayo district,\nlanded on a snow covered shelf 200\nfeet below and escaped with three\nbroken ribs. Word of the accident was\nreceived here today.\nII OF\nWomen's Bureau Director Says\nWomen Are Held in War\ntime Jobs.\nto!for instance lathe operators. Thou\nI sands of women became very efficient\njand still retain their places beside men\noperators. The war gave American\nChicago.\u2014(Correspondence of The\nAssociated Press.)\u2014Only part of the\nwomen engaged in industry during the\nwar period have lost their places\nthrough the return of men from the\nwar and the lack of employment. Miss\nMary Anderson, director of the wo\nmen's bureau of the United States\ndepartment of labor, reports.\n'Statements to the bureau from hun\ndreds of industry heads who employed\nonly women during the war show they\nhave retained their female help, while\nothers state they have replaced their\nwomen with male workers,\" Miss An\nderson said.\nNo Figures Obtainable.\n\"Because of the volume of unem\nployment throughout the country today\nno accurate figures as to the number\nof women employed in industries at\npresent as compared with the war per\niod are obtainable.\n\"I believe that when figures of the\n1020 census are available, they will\nshow more than 12,000,000 women in\ngainful occupation. The census, how\never. will not set forth the present\nsituation because unemployment has\nincreased by leaps and bounds since it\nwas taken.\nWomen Fill Positions.\n\"Women won the admiration of em\nployers during the war period by their\nability to fill in on men's jobs. Take\nwomen a new opportunity in industry\nand they grasped it.\"\nThere are two factors needed to\ninsure women their plnce in industry,\nMiss Anderson said. Protective legis\nlation for the eight, hour day is badly\nneeded, she declared, and added that\nthe women must \"organize within the\nnext few years.\"\nWith the return of prosperity, indus\ntries will ^clamor for women workers,\nin the opinion of Miss Mary E. Mc\nDowell of the University of Chicago\nSettlement house, who is chairman of\nthe women in industry committee of\nthe National League of Women Voters.\nPRAYERS NEEDED\"\nVisitor\u2014\"What does the chaplain\ndo here?\"\nFreshman\u2014\"Oh, he gets up in\nchapel every morning, looks over the\nstudent body, and they prays for the\ncollege.\"\u2014Lehigh Burr.\nKeeping GrowingFeet Hsppy\nSCHOOL TIME\nThe first days In school ara\n\u2022ronderfnl dayi\u2014\"Billy Damps\"\nor \"Betay Bouncer.\" Need we\nimpress upon you the Import\nance of shoes that are absolute\nly comfortable? You know how\n\u2022hoes that hart simply \"kill\"\nyour own enthusiasm.\nIn the fifth last for children,\nthe Inner line ot the sole heclns\nto take shape slightly similar\nto that of m \"grown-up's\" shoe.\nThe toes are broad, the heels\nlow, and the whole shoe very\nsturdily built.\nFLAHERTY\nPERRA\nIS Third Street South\nT\nin\nTo Complete Federal\nHighway Project in\nMissoula County\nSpecial to The Tribune.\nMissoula, March 2.\u2014District En\ngineer Fred Thieme of the forest ser\nvice has announced that the secretary\nof agriculture has approved the execu\ntion of a co-operative agreement for\nthe construction of the Cold Springs\nsection of the West Gallatin road. This\nwill be the sixth section of that stretch\nof highway, of which 13.3 miles are\nnow completed. It is planned to con\nstruct four sections of the Gallatin\nhighway during the coming field sea\nson, bringing the road through the\ncanyon and opening it for traffic.\nWhile the construction work is going\non it will be necessary to close the\nroad for travel as was the case last\nseason.\nGame Warden Asks\nDeputy to Resign\nin Lincoln County\nSpecial to The Tribune.\nLibby, March 2.\u2014 L. T. Hunter of\nLibby, who for the last two years has\nheld the position of deputy game war\nden for Lincoln county, last week was\nasked by M. W. Porter, state game\nwarden, to resign. Mr. Hunter com\nplied and, at this time, the position\nof deputy game warden is vacant. As\npart of the work he has accomplished,\nhe brought into this country during his\nterm 3,000,000 fish fry.\n17 Women Tip Over\nin Libby Sleighride\nSpecial to The Tribune.\nLibby, March 2.\u2014A team belonging\nto Henry Boothman. up-river ranciier,\nand driven to a sleigh by his son, Bill,\nbecame unmanageable on the road be\ntween the Boothman place and Libby\nFriday afternoon, and ran away, with\nthe result that 17 members of the\nPresbyterian Ladies' Aid society were\nthrown o.ut. The only serious injury\nsuffered in the accident was caused to\nMrs. A. C. Herbst, whose right arm\nwns broken between the shoulder and\nthe elbow.\nJOINS MISSOULA OFFICE.\nSpecial to The Tribune.\nMissoula, March 2.\u2014P. L. Barstow\nof Idaho Falls. Idaho, succeeded A.\nIlopper as manager of the Western\nUnion telegraph office here. Mr. Hop\nper, who has been in charge of the of\nfice for the last eight months, resign\ned to manage his property which he has j\npurchased in Orchard Homes.\nREDUCE YOUR FAT\nWITHOUT DIETING\nYears ago the formula for fat reduc\ntion was \"diet\"\u2014\"exercise.\" Today It is\n\"Take Marmola Prescription Tablets.\"\nFriends tell friends\u2014doctors tell their\npatients, until thousands know and use\nthis convenient, harmless method. They\neat what they like, live as they like,,\nand still lose their two, three or four\npounds of fat a week. Simple, effec\ntive. harmless Marmola Prescription\nTablets are sold by all druggists\u2014a\nlarge case for one dollar. Or If you\nprefer you may write direct to the\nMarmola Company, 4612 Woodward\nAve., Detroit,*Mich.\nQUICK RELIEF\nGet Dr. Edw ards' O live Tablets\nThat is the joyful cry of thousands\nsince Dr. Edwards produced Olive\nTablets, the substitute for calomel. No\ngriping results from these pleasant\nlittle tablets. They cause the liver\nand bowels to act normally. They\nnever force them to unnatural action.\nDr. Edwards' Olive Tablets are a\nsoothing, healing, vegetable compound\nmixed with olive oil.\nIf you have a bad taste, bad breath,\nfeel dull, tired, are constipated or\nbilious, you'll find quick and sure re\nsults from Dr. Edwards' little Olive\nTablets at bedtime. 15c and 30c. a box.\nRely on Cuticura\nTo Clear Away\nSkin Troubles\nSoap to danie, Ointment ta Moth* .Tatam to paw\nAu, 3c. Samples of OrtUu\u00bb. Deyt. X, Km.\nSHE SAVED A\n\"RUN ON BANK\"\nProtected Family Savings by\n\"Diamond Dyeing\" old\nGarments. Draperies\nAny woman can follow the simple\ndirections in package and dinraond-dye\nshabby, faded skirts, waists, coats,\nstockings, sweaters, coverings, hang\nings, everything into new. Don't risk\nyour material in a poor dye that streaks\nor spots. Buy Diamond Dyes\"\u2014no\nother kind. Tell druggist whether your\nmaterial is wool or silk, or if it is\ncotton, linen, or a mixture. 16 rich,\nfadeless colors.\nThe invention of the magic lantern\nis ascribed to Roger Bacon about\n1260.\n1\nSIFE HIDING PUCE\nFederal Prohibition 1 Officers\nSay Arrests in Range Dis\ntricts Are Difficult.\nHelena, March 2.\u2014 The Koeky moun\ntains. familiarly known as the back\nbone of the continent, loom as the\nbackbone of the illicit liquor manu\nfacture, in the opinion of X. D. Miller,\nlof Denver, assistant field supervisor\nof federal prohibition forces in the\nintermountain states, who was in\nHelena recently. Mr. Miller's district,\nhe stated, includes 10 states and ex\ntends along the Rocky mountain range\nfrom the Canadian line to the southern\nborder of Colorado.\n\"It will be years before the stills\ncan be rooted from the mountains,\"\nsaid Mr. Miller. \"The seclusion that\nthe mountains afford and the places\nthat are virtually imposible to ap\nproach without being discovered by\nmoonshiners, will make the job of eli\nminating these stills a hard one.\n\"Prohibition is not a failure. We\nare working against great odds, but\nprogress in enforcement is being made.\nIt will take time to make prohibition\nand we do not expect it to reach its\nbest state for a generation.\"\nFALLS FROM SWING,\nBREAKING ARM.\nAgawam, March 2.\u2014 John Gericli,\nyoungest son of Mr. and Mrs. Nick\nGerich of this place, fell out of a\nschool swing last week, breaking an\narm. He has been taken to a hos\npital in CBoteau.\nTime to Re-roof\nI\nT'S a comfortable feeling\nduring these days of blustery\nweather to know that your\nroof will withstand the battering\nof the elements. The fiercest\nMarch gale cannot tear loose a\nNelson Roof. If your roof is\nleaky and the shingles are loose,\nthe time to re-roof is now before\nany damage is done. If you\nwait, it may mean heavy repair\nbills not only on the roof but\ninside where water may have\ncrept through and stained up\nthe ceilings.\nA new roof, like a new bon\nnet, greatly enhances the charm\nof what lies under it. A Nelson\nRoof is a roof of lasting beauty.\nThere is a Nelson Roof for\nevery type of building. Your\nlumber dealer will be glad to go\nover your roofing problems\nwith you and show you how\nNelson Roofs meet every re\nquirement. Write us for sam\nples and the illustrated booklet,\n\"The Pr\u00f6of of a Roof\" contain\ning an interesting story of roof\ning progress.\nB. F. Nelson Mfg. Co.\n435 Main St. N. E.\nMinneapolis\nDurable\nBeautiful\nFire-resisting\nEccnomical\nNelson\nFt O\nFergus County Sues\nJudith Basin for\nReturn of $50,000\nSpecial to The Tribune.\nLewistown, March 2.\u2014Fergus county\nis about to institute an action against\n.Judith Basin county to recover some\n\u2022V>0,000 excess school money alleged to\nhave been paid the new county, \u00bbhe\nerror arising, it is explained, through\nsettling upon a valuation instead of a\nper capita basis. It is understood that\ninstructions as to the proceeding were\nreceived from the attorney general and\nthe suit will be brought by County At\ntorney E. J. Baker.\nSentenced to Die,\nbut Wants His Teeth\nin Sound Condition\nSpecial to The Tribune.\nButte, March 2.\u2014Theodore Chronos,\nheld under sentence of death at the\ncounty jail for complicity in the mur\nder of Stephen Prenatt at his home\nhere on December 8, 1919, is permitted\nto make weekly trips to a local busi\nness block, where he is receiving treat\nment from a dentist. In handcuffs he\nmakes these trips on foot in the cus\ntody of a deputy sheriff. Report has\nit he is paying for his treatments from\nhis own funds.\nVALIER EPIDEMIC NOT\nAS BAD AS REPORTED.\nSpecial to The Tribune.\nValier, March 2.\u2014Reports of a\nsmallpox epidemic in Valier are being\nspread by misinformed people and are\nwithout a foundation, according to a\nlocal doctor, who stated that there is\nno cause for alarm although some peo\nple are looking at it in that light. The\nreport that there were 20 cases of the\ndisease here was probably based on the\nfact that there are several cases and\nthree households are under quaran\ntine.\nSeveral Hundred Dollars in\nClothing and Valuables\nTaken From Homes.\nButte, March 2.\u2014 Drastic orders are\nunderstood to have been issued here\nTuesday night by police officials for\na general roundup of all suspicious\ncharacters following a wave of rob\nberies which have swept over the city\nduring last^week and which culminat\ned Monday night in several homes be\ning entered during the absence of own\ners and the taking of hundreds of dol\nlars in clothing and valuables.\nA church was also entered and sev\neral hundred dollars worth of plumb\ning fixtures removed. No trace of the\nburglars has been found by the offi\ncers.\nTo< combat the operations of the\n7=\nU U ffl-u (A M M frr P m m gi m frj H U\n<\u00aeage\n&pecialj>\n\u00e4fiop\n417 Central\nSnlk Chemise\nSpe\u00f4aSTodlay Only\n$3o\u00ae5\nfr? w to 1 0 H to to H\ncrook\u00ab, a motorcycle \u00abquad of nia* wm\nformed Tuesday. They work in*\nshifts of 8 boors\u00bb 3 to a drift la patrol\nling the residence districts.. One offi-i\ncer who has been assigned to ibe sQnad\nwas injured Tuesday afternoon when,\na tire of his cycle barst, while he was;\npursuing a speeding automobile, throw\ning him heavily to the pavement\nValier to Increase\nIts Water Supply\n\nSpecial to The Tribune.\nValier, March 2.\u2014 In preparation\nfor expected growth of 'the town In\nthe near future, Valier is prospect\ning for an additional water supply.\nIt. W. Speir, Jr., of the engineering\nforce of the Valier Montana Land ft\nWater Co., has been directing the field\nwork of a party investigating rock\nformations along Birch creek about\nfour miles northwest of Valier where\nthey expect to find evidence of a water\nbearing formation dipping under the\ntown at a depth not too great for an\neconomical well. Valier intends that\nthere shall be no water shortage due\nto unpreparedness.\nTRY A LOAF OF PURITY BREAD\nFROM YOUR 6R0CER.\u2014ADV.\n7=","height":"23016","width":"19416"}}
